<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,1955,2020]" box="[198,1436,1955,1981]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
In the SEM, the exterior of the valve is dominated with striae composed of two rows of areolae (
<figureCitation box="[1319,1436,1955,1981]" captionStart="PLATE 17" captionStartId="19.[151,230,1766,1787]" captionTargetBox="[186,1394,641,1729]" captionTargetId="figure-313@19.[151,1436,622,1767]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="PLATE 17, FIGURES 102–108. G. distorta, SEM. Figs 103–105, external views. Figs 103, 105. Apices showing doubly-punctate striae and, at the footpole, apical pore field with porelli similar to the areolae. Fig. 104. Central area with dilated proximal raphe ends and striae tapering from biseriate to uniseriate. Figs 102, 106–108, internal view. Fig. 102. Entire valve view. Note prominent helictoglossae and central nodule. Fig. 106. Headpole with helictoglossa slightly offset from main axis of raphe. Fig. 107. Raised central nodule with proximal raphe ends deflected in the same direction. Internal thickenings are evident in the striae near the axial area. Fig. 108. Footpole, with prominent helictoglossa, small pseudoseptum and thin interstriae dividing the porelli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5077650" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5077650/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Figs 103–</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,1955,2020]" lastBlockId="19.[151,1436,152,564]" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
105). The headpole has striae that extend onto the mantle, and the distal raphe end is deflected slightly before reaching the apex and extending onto the mantle (
<figureCitation box="[740,843,152,178]" captionStart="PLATE 17" captionStartId="19.[151,230,1766,1787]" captionTargetBox="[186,1394,641,1729]" captionTargetId="figure-313@19.[151,1436,622,1767]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="PLATE 17, FIGURES 102–108. G. distorta, SEM. Figs 103–105, external views. Figs 103, 105. Apices showing doubly-punctate striae and, at the footpole, apical pore field with porelli similar to the areolae. Fig. 104. Central area with dilated proximal raphe ends and striae tapering from biseriate to uniseriate. Figs 102, 106–108, internal view. Fig. 102. Entire valve view. Note prominent helictoglossae and central nodule. Fig. 106. Headpole with helictoglossa slightly offset from main axis of raphe. Fig. 107. Raised central nodule with proximal raphe ends deflected in the same direction. Internal thickenings are evident in the striae near the axial area. Fig. 108. Footpole, with prominent helictoglossa, small pseudoseptum and thin interstriae dividing the porelli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5077650" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5077650/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 103</figureCitation>
). The central area has dilated proximal raphe ends and striae that are biseriate near the margins but taper to uniseriate striae towards the axial area and central area (
<figureCitation box="[216,318,229,255]" captionStart="PLATE 17" captionStartId="19.[151,230,1766,1787]" captionTargetBox="[186,1394,641,1729]" captionTargetId="figure-313@19.[151,1436,622,1767]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="PLATE 17, FIGURES 102–108. G. distorta, SEM. Figs 103–105, external views. Figs 103, 105. Apices showing doubly-punctate striae and, at the footpole, apical pore field with porelli similar to the areolae. Fig. 104. Central area with dilated proximal raphe ends and striae tapering from biseriate to uniseriate. Figs 102, 106–108, internal view. Fig. 102. Entire valve view. Note prominent helictoglossae and central nodule. Fig. 106. Headpole with helictoglossa slightly offset from main axis of raphe. Fig. 107. Raised central nodule with proximal raphe ends deflected in the same direction. Internal thickenings are evident in the striae near the axial area. Fig. 108. Footpole, with prominent helictoglossa, small pseudoseptum and thin interstriae dividing the porelli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5077650" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5077650/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 104</figureCitation>
). The apical pore fields have porelli in distinct rows and extend all over the mantle (
<figureCitation box="[1305,1408,229,255]" captionStart="PLATE 17" captionStartId="19.[151,230,1766,1787]" captionTargetBox="[186,1394,641,1729]" captionTargetId="figure-313@19.[151,1436,622,1767]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="PLATE 17, FIGURES 102–108. G. distorta, SEM. Figs 103–105, external views. Figs 103, 105. Apices showing doubly-punctate striae and, at the footpole, apical pore field with porelli similar to the areolae. Fig. 104. Central area with dilated proximal raphe ends and striae tapering from biseriate to uniseriate. Figs 102, 106–108, internal view. Fig. 102. Entire valve view. Note prominent helictoglossae and central nodule. Fig. 106. Headpole with helictoglossa slightly offset from main axis of raphe. Fig. 107. Raised central nodule with proximal raphe ends deflected in the same direction. Internal thickenings are evident in the striae near the axial area. Fig. 108. Footpole, with prominent helictoglossa, small pseudoseptum and thin interstriae dividing the porelli." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5077650" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5077650/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 105</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[151,1436,152,564]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Internally, the valve interior has prominent helictoglossae and pseudosepta at the poles (Figs 102, 106, 108). The central part of the valve has a slightly raised central nodule, where deflected proximal raphe ends occur. Striae become uniseriate near the axial area, and in this region strong thickenings are evident (Fig. 107).</paragraph>
